Erik&#x27;s example of the using statement is a straw-man: you get exactly the same problems if you do this:<p>using(var file = File.Open(path))
{
    _someField = file;
}<p>..and then use _someField in another method.<p>It&#x27;s not so much a problem with understanding closures, but of the limitations of IDisposable.

And they&#x27;d both be five lines shorter if the fibonacci implementation weren&#x27;t overcomplicated, making your gain even more significant (8 lines vs 17).<p><pre><code>  let Fibbonacci = SequenceOf {

    var current = 0, next = 1

    return GeneratorOf {
      var ret = current
      current = next
      next = next + ret
      return ret
    }
  }</code></pre>
